This is a textbook Wayland clipboard "handshake" failure. Chromium on Hyprland is likely running in XWayland (X11 emulation) mode by default, while your image is sitting in a native Wayland clipboard buffer. They aren't talking to each other.

Here is how to bridge that gap and get it working.

1. Force Chromium into Native Wayland
If Chromium is running via XWayland, it won't see the wl-clipboard data.

Open Chromium and go to: chrome://flags

Search for Preferred Ozone platform

Change it from "Default" to Wayland

Restart Chromium completely.

2. The "Middleman" Fix (Use a Clipboard Manager)
Wayland clipboard data is only "offered" by an app while it's open. If you take a screenshot and the screenshot tool closes, the data vanishes. You need a daemon to "hold" that image for you.

Install cliphist: sudo pacman -S cliphist

Add these to your hyprland.conf:

Bash
exec-once = wl-paste --type text --watch cliphist store 
exec-once = wl-paste --type image --watch cliphist store
This ensures that images are stored in a persistent buffer that both Wayland and XWayland apps can access.

3. Verify the Format
If it still says "something went wrong," Chromium might be picky about the "mime-type" of the PNG. You can manually push the image into the clipboard in a way Chromium definitely understands:

Bash
wl-copy -t image/png < /path/to/your/image.png
4. If you are using grimblast or slurp
If you're taking screenshots and trying to paste them immediately, ensure your screenshot command includes the -t image/png flag or is piped correctly. For example:
grim -g "$(slurp)" - | wl-copy

